=== vim-OS Roadmap ===

Far Goal:
A minimal graphical OS booting into a window manager controlled entirely via
keyboard — vim-style:
  :q         -> close focused app (or shutdown if no app open)
  /pattern   -> search/focus app by name
  j/k        -> cycle windows
  :n         -> new terminal window
  No mouse. Everything is keyboard-driven.

PHASE 0 — BOOT FOUNDATION

[X] 0.1 — Kernel stack
    entry() uses the bootloader's stack. Set up your own 16 KiB BSS stack
    and switch RSP to it at the top of entry().

[X] 0.2 — Serial output (COM1)
    Write putchar/printf over port 0x3F8. Critical for debugging everything
    below. Keep this and use it constantly.

[X] 0.3 — GDT
    Kernel code/data segments + TSS. Needed for interrupts and later for
    user-mode apps.


PHASE 1 — INTERRUPTS & TIMER

[X] 1.1 — IDT
     256 entries. Install handlers for:
       IRQ0  → PIT timer
       IRQ1  → PS/2 keyboard
       Exceptions (0-31) → print error + halt

[X] 1.2 — PIC (8259A)
     Remap IRQs 0-15 to INT 0x20-0x2F. Mask everything except IRQ0, IRQ1.
     Note: Must disable local APIC (IA32_APIC_BASE MSR bit 11) under UEFI/OVMF,
     otherwise the PIC's output gets swallowed by the APIC.

[X] 1.3 — PIT timer
     Program channel 0 at ~100 Hz. Provide timer_sleep(ms) spin-loop.


PHASE 2 — MEMORY MANAGEMENT

[X] 2.1 — Physical Memory Manager
    Use Limine memmap request. Bitmap allocator tracking 4 KiB frames.
    pmm_alloc() / pmm_free().

[X] 2.2 — Paging (4-level)
    PML4 → PDP → PD → PT. Kernel at 0xffffffff80000000 (higher half).
    vmm_map_page() for mapping arbitrary physical pages.

[X] 2.3 — Heap allocator
    Start with a bump allocator, then free-list. Provide malloc()/free()
    for dynamic data structures.


PHASE 3 — KEYBOARD

[X] 3.1 — PS/2 Keyboard driver
    Read scancodes from port 0x60 on IRQ1.
    Convert scancode set 1 → ASCII.
    Track Shift, Ctrl, Alt, Caps Lock.
    Provide a ring buffer of key events.
    (No mouse — skip PS/2 mouse entirely.)


PHASE 4 — GRAPHICS LAYER

[X] 4.1 — Font & primitives
    Embed a monospace 8×16 bitmap font (font8x16.h, auto-generated).
    Functions: gfx_clear(), gfx_rect(), gfx_char(), gfx_str() on framebuffer.
    Integrated into main.c — displays "Hello from opencode OS!" on boot.

[ ] 4.2 — Double buffering (optional)
    Backbuffer + memcpy to hardware framebuffer on vsync. Prevents tearing.


PHASE 5 — SHELL

[ ] 5.1 — Terminal widget
    Scrollable text region on framebuffer. Cursor, newline, backspace,
    keyboard echo. Input line buffer (editable).

[ ] 5.2 — Command parser & builtins
    Parse a command string. Built-ins: help, echo, clear, reboot, ps.


PHASE 6 — WINDOW MANAGER

[X] 6.1 — Tiling window manager
    Fixed-size array (WM_MAX=8) of windows, windows[0] = focused.
    Recursive alternating-split layout: V[0 | H[1 | V[2 | H[3 | ...]]]].
    1px gap between windows.

[X] 6.2 — Compositor
    Clear screen, fill each window rect with its theme color via gfx_rect.
    No title bars or chrome. 

[X] 6.3 — Focus management
    j/k cycle focus by rotating the array.
    :q + Enter closes focused window; if only one remains, shut down.

[X] 6.4 — Window creation (:n)
    Spawn new windows bound to a C content function.

[X] 6.5 — Vim command bar (optional)
    :  → command mode, / → search mode, Escape to cancel.

